title: Define `_.sum()` behavior for non-numbers, NaNs and an empty array?
body:
I'm not actually using lodash, just saw _.sum in some stackoverflow example and got curious how it behaves on edge cases.  Turns out these edge cases changed in 4.0; neither old nor new behaviors were documented (just says ["Computes the sum of the values in array"](https://lodash.com/docs#sum)).  Don't know which of the behaviors you want to commit to, but it would be useful to at least document the change...

In 3.10.1 [https://jsfiddle.net/1yp8rzcz/1/], the code summed essentially `+item || 0`, resulting in:

```
[] -> 0
["a"] -> 0
["a", 42] -> 42
[NaN] -> 0
[NaN, 42] -> 42
```

(personal opinion: skipping non-numbers sounds handy, but it's surprising that a sum involving NaN doesn't reture NaN)

On post-4.0.0 master, it uses simple `+`, with `(array && array.length) ? baseSum(array, identity) : undefined` causing undefined for empty arrays  [https://jsfiddle.net/dseph7L6/2/]:

```
[] -> undefined
["a"] -> a
["a", 42] -> a42
[NaN] -> NaN
[NaN, 42] -> NaN
```

(personal opinion: using simple `a[0] + a[1] +...+ a[n]` semantics is probably good as it's least-surprising; but I'd call `sum([])` returning `undefined` a clear bug — IMNSHO it must be 0!)

title: Note: Breaking Change in behaviour of filter between v3 and v4
body:
Here's two node REPLs showing the behaviour of filter in version 3 and version 4 (in particular, I was previously using 3.10.1 and upgraded to 4.0.0 and the change broke my code which relied on this signature. 
- Version 3

'''

> lodash.filter([{hello:"world"}], "hello", "world")
> [ { hello: 'world' } ]
> lodash.filter([{hello:"world"}], "hello", "mars")
> []
> '''
- Version 4

```
> lodash.filter([{hello:"world"}], "hello", "world")
[ { hello: 'world' } ]
> lodash.filter([{hello:"world"}], "hello", "mars")
[ { hello: 'world' } ]
```

I cannot see where this change in behaviour is documented in the changelog. There's a comment about _.where being deprecated in favour of _.filter, but there doesn't seem to be a statement about the behaviour of _.filter itself changing.

The new syntax equivalent of the three-arg signature seems to be this two-arg signature instead...

```
lodash.filter([{hello:"world"}], {hello:"world"})
```

This is just an issue so that people can confirm the change if they encounter it independently. Close if this is an intended breaking change.

body:
When I precompile templates with `lodash-cli` `4.0.0` and use Lodash 4.0.0 Core build, I do get error:

```
Uncaught TypeError: _.assign is not a function
```

If I use previous `lodash-cli` `3.10.1` the templates work even with Lodash 4.0.0 Core.

It seems that `lodash-cli` `4.0.0` generates at the end of the template this:

``` javascript
_.templates=_.assign(_.templates||{},templates)
```

While `3.10.1` generates something like this:

``` javascript
_.templates=_.extend(_.templates||{},templates)
```

So either the `assign` (there seems to be `assignIn`) is missing from the Core build or the precompilation doesn't generate right output.

title: isEqual broken in 4.0.0 - ordering of object properties matters
body:
Using lodash 3.10.1

``` js
var obj1 = {'a':'a', 'b':'b'}
var obj2 = {'a':'a', 'b':'b'}
var l = require('lodash')
l.isEqual(obj1,obj2)
true
var obj3 = {'b':'b', 'a':'a'}
l.isEqual(obj1,obj3)
true
```

Using lodash 4.0.0

``` js
var obj1 = {'a':'a', 'b':'b'}
var obj2 = {'a':'a', 'b':'b'}
var l = require('lodash')
l.isEqual(obj1,obj2)
true
var obj3 = {'b':'b', 'a':'a'}
l.isEqual(obj1,obj3)
false
```

Example:

``` js
> var obj1 = {'a':'a', 'b':'b'}
undefined
> var obj2 = {'a':'a', 'b':'b'}
undefined
> var l_3 = require('lodash_3_10_1')
undefined
> var l_4 = require('lodash')
undefined
> var obj3 = {'b':'b', 'a':'a'}
undefined
> l_3.isEqual(obj1, obj2)
true
> l_3.isEqual(obj1, obj3)
true
> l_4.isEqual(obj1, obj2)
true
> l_4.isEqual(obj1, obj3)
false
```

title: _.fromPairs treats pair keys as an object path
body:
The docs say (emphasis mine):

> The inverse of _.toPairs; this method returns an object composed from **key**-value pairs.

It's not acting as the inverse when keys contain `.`, as it's splitting keys on `.` and creating nested objects:

```
$ node
> var ld = require('lodash');
undefined
> ld.VERSION
'4.0.0'
> var pairs = ld.toPairs({'foo.bar': {b: 123}, b: 9})
undefined
> pairs
[ [ 'foo.bar', { b: 123 } ], [ 'b', 9 ] ]
> ld.fromPairs(pairs)
{ foo: { bar: { b: 123 } }, b: 9 }
```

3.10.1 behaviour:

```
$ node
> var ld = require('lodash')
undefined
> ld.VERSION
'3.10.1'
> var pairs = ld.pairs({'foo.bar': {b: 123}, b: 9})
undefined
> pairs
[ [ 'foo.bar', { b: 123 } ], [ 'b', 9 ] ]
> ld.object(pairs)
{ 'foo.bar': { b: 123 }, b: 9 }
```

Curry placeholder in lodash/fp
body:
It would be nice if lodash/fp could alias `curry.placeholder` to either `_` or `__`, as in:

``` js
import {_, add} from 'lodash/fp' // or __
add(_, 2)(3) // => 5
```

Because it's overly verbose to do:

``` js
import {curry, add} from 'lodash/fp'
add(curry.placeholder, 2)(3) // => 5
```

The following works, but it's surprising and semantically weird to have to do this. It also prevents tree-shaking if a shakeable `fp` ever finds its way into `lodash-es`.

``` js
import _, {add} from 'lodash/fp'
add(_, 2)(3) // => 5
```

(We currently lint against importing the monolith `_`, preferring named imports.)

title: In lodash/fp, `flow`, `flowRight`, etc. should implement auto-currying
body:
In fp, in general), functions created by `pipe` and `compose` are automatically curried.

``` js
const times = (a, b) => a * b
const plusFive = c => c + 5

// lodash/fp
const timesPlusFive = pipe(times, plusFive)
timesPlusFive(5, 3) // => 20
timesPlusFive(5)(3) // => TypeError (timesPlusFive isn't curried)
```

Thoughts on aligning these?

title: lodash.union depends on nonexistant version of lodash._arrayincludes
body:
As you can see lodash.union depends on lodash_arrayincludes ^3.0.0

```
> npm info lodash.union

{ name: 'lodash.union',
  description: 'The lodash method `_.union` exported as a module.',
  'dist-tags': { latest: '4.0.0' },

... 
 dependencies: 
   { 'lodash._arrayincludes': '^3.0.0',
     'lodash._arrayincludeswith': '^3.0.0',
     'lodash._baseflatten': '^4.0.0',
     'lodash._cachehas': '^3.0.0',
     'lodash._setcache': '^3.0.0',
     'lodash.rest': '^4.0.0' },

}
```

However there is only a 4.0.0 on npm

```
> npm info lodash._arrayincludes

{ name: 'lodash._arrayincludes',
  description: 'The internal lodash function `arrayIncludes` exported as a module.',
  'dist-tags': { latest: '4.0.0' },
  versions: [ '4.0.0' ]
...
}
```

title: [website] Minified build download link points to 'compat' build
body:
Looks like https://lodash.com/#download links are incorrect:
- Core build (4kB minified) → As expected, links to https://raw.github.com/lodash/lodash/4.0.0/dist/lodash.core.js and https://raw.github.com/lodash/lodash/4.0.0/dist/lodash.core.min.js
- Full build (20kB minified) → First link is https://raw.github.com/lodash/lodash/4.0.0/dist/lodash.js (good), but 'minified' link goes to lodash-compat rather than lodash : https://raw.github.com/lodash/lodash-compat/4.0.0/lodash.min.js

Sounds wrong, right?

title: Needs to address zipObject v.s. fromPairs backwards incompatibility on Changelog
body:
It seems that in `3.1.0`, `zipObject` accepts a single array:
https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/3.10.1/doc/README.md#_zipobjectprops-values

But in `4.0.0`, it only accepts two arrays, and `fromPairs` is now used for single array arguments.
https://lodash.com/docs#zipObject
https://lodash.com/docs#fromPairs

This seems like a backwards-incompatible change but it doesn't seem to be documented here:
https://github.com/lodash/lodash/wiki/Changelog#compatibility-warnings

Wanted to confirm before making any changes on the wiki.

title: Arguments for pickBy predicate
body: It seems that the `pickBy` function in latest version (4.0.0) doesn't provide the `(value, key)` arguments as before. Is this intentional or something that still needs to be implemented?

title: Auto Currying in lodash/fp
body:
Is this a bug or is my understanding of the new `lodash/fp` incorrect. Can I call `isEqual` as if it is auto-curried?

``` Javascript
const isEqual = require('lodash/fp').isEqual;

console.log(isEqual(1, 1)) // true
console.log(isEqual(1)) // false ???
console.log(isEqual(1)(1)) // Error
```

title: Wrong dependency in lodash.merge
body:
`lodash.merge` depends on `lodash._stack@3.0.0` which is not published at all. 

Source: https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/npm-packages/lodash.merge/package.json#L20

So if one tries to install `lodash.merge` npm will fail with:

```
npm ERR! No compatible version found: lodash._stack@^3.0.0
npm ERR! Valid install targets:
npm ERR! ["4.0.0"]
```

IMHO the required version should be `4.0.0`!?

now


I can't find this in the changelog.. so is it intentional or a bug?

title: Lodash/fp `prop` alias is surprising
body:
In Lodash/fp, `property` is aliased to `prop`. This yields kind of surprising behavior:

``` js
// in lodash/fp
prop('a')({a: 1}) // => 1
prop('a', {a: 1}) // => a function, since `property` is 1-ary
```

Perhaps `get` should be aliased to `prop` instead?

title: Lodash/fp's merge signature is surprising
body:
Lodash/fp's `merge(a, b)` merges `a` onto `b`.

Is this intentional? I can see both arguments as to whether `a` or `b` should be considered the data argument -- it's just kind of surprising. Might be worth documenting.

title: Error in _.range doc
body:
```
If end is less than start a zero-length range is created  
unless a negative step is specified.
```

looks not to be true.

`_.range(0, -5)` gives `[0, -1, -2, -3, -4]`

title: Flip arguments in split
body:
Couldn't find this listed in any other issues, but perhaps I'm looking in the wrong place. For some reason I can't post issues in lodash/fp, and my understanding is that lodash/fp and lodash are merging. Happy to change where this is posted if it's not listed correctly.

``` js
import { flow, flip, map, capitalize, toUpper, take, split } from 'lodash/fp'

const initials = flow(
  (s => s.split(' ')),
  map(take(1)),
  map(toUpper)
)
```

it seems to make more sense to flip the arguments so I can use 

``` js
import { flow, flip, map, capitalize, toUpper, take, split } from 'lodash/fp'

const initials = flow(
  split(' '),
  map(take(1)),
  map(toUpper)
)
```

splitting on the value isn't as valuable with this paradigm of coding as a curried function to split something

title: Can the version 3 docs be put online?
body:
Congratulations on publishing version 4! I will definitely be taking a look at it.

But until we all migrate our projects over, could you please add the version 3 docs back online?

(If anyone else is looking for them, you can read them [here](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/tree/3.10.1/doc).)

title: _.flatten function changed?
body:
Hi, I wrote a small piece of code for test _.flatten. the code is as below

``` js
objects = [{ 'a': [1] }, { 'a': [2, 3] }];
console.log(_.flatten(objects, 'a')); 
version<=2.4.2 the result is [ 1, 2, 3 ]
```

but while I use version>=3.0.0 result is `[ { a: [ 1 ] }, { a: [ 2, 3 ] } ]`

I got some confused here, is there any definition change for this function?

So I try `_.flattenDeep`, the result is the same==> `[ { a: [ 1 ] }, { a: [ 2, 3 ] } ]`

Is there any compatible way to return `[1,2,3]` as usual?
